<!-- PIPELINE -->
<div class="wrap">
<section class="section reveal">
  <p class="sec-label">Architecture</p>
  <h2 class="sec-title">The Full Data Pipeline</h2>
  <p class="sec-body">Two systems, two formats, zero shared schema out of the box. The pipeline was designed so every downstream step inherits structure from the one before it — not the other way around.</p>

  <div class="pipe-grid">
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">01</div>
      <span class="step-name">MATLAB</span>
      <p>Automated ingestion of SN and ADO CSVs, date validation, null removal, string normalization, cross-system ID mapping, and SLA aging computation</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">02</div>
      <span class="step-name">MySQL Workbench</span>
      <p>Enriched tables loaded into a relational schema with foreign keys linking SN ticket numbers to ADO enhancement IDs — schema defined once, enforced at the DB layer</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">03</div>
      <span class="step-name">Power Query</span>
      <p>Power BI connects via the SQL Server connector and inherits column types and joins automatically — no manual field remapping on every refresh</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">04</div>
      <span class="step-name">Power BI</span>
      <p>Two dashboards on a clean data model — Customer view for external stakeholders and Internal view for tracking delivery efficiency across teams</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sql-box reveal">
    <h3>// Why route through SQL at all</h3>
    <p>
      MATLAB exports clean CSVs but Power BI has no way to know what the columns mean — every refresh would require manually re-specifying types, joins, and relationships inside Power Query. That breaks under team use and doesn't scale to new data sources.<br><br>
      Pushing to MySQL first means <strong>the schema lives at the database layer</strong>, not inside a BI tool. Power BI connects once and inherits everything. It also means any analyst can write queries directly against the same data independently of the dashboard — <strong>the database is the source of truth, not the visualization</strong>.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
</div>

<!-- STATS -->
<div class="wrap">
<section class="section reveal">
  <p class="sec-label">Dataset</p>
  <h2 class="sec-title">By the Numbers</h2>
  <div class="stats">
    <div class="stat"><span class="stat-n">2</span><span class="stat-l">Source systems merged<br>(ServiceNow + ADO)</span></div>
    <div class="stat"><span class="stat-n">78%</span><span class="stat-l">Cross-system traceability rate — 22% flagged and excluded</span></div>
    <div class="stat"><span class="stat-n">56.9%</span><span class="stat-l">Enhancement closure rate across all tracked tickets</span></div>
    <div class="stat"><span class="stat-n">7</span><span class="stat-l">ADO assignees with workload distribution modeled</span></div>
  </div>
</section>
</div>

<!-- EDA -->
<div class="wrap">
<section class="section reveal">
  <p class="sec-label">Exploratory Data Analysis</p>
  <h2 class="sec-title">Pre-Dashboard Analysis in MATLAB</h2>
  <p class="eda-intro">
    The EDA phase wasn't cosmetic. Each analysis below directly shaped a decision in the final dashboard design — the workload imbalance finding drove the assignee filter, the aging distribution drove the SLA highlight in the completion chart, and the traceability check determined what data was even safe to use.
  </p>

  <div class="eda-grid">
    <div class="eda-card">
      <div class="eda-head">
        <div class="eda-title">Enhancement State Distribution</div>
        <div class="eda-desc">56.9% closed is a healthy signal, but 19.4% still active and 12.5% new means roughly 1 in 3 tickets is unresolved at any snapshot. The "Awaiting Customer" slice — small but persistent — flags a process gap where tickets stall waiting on client input with no automated escalation.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="c1" height="190"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <div class="eda-card">
      <div class="eda-head">
        <div class="eda-title">Workload by ADO Assignee</div>
        <div class="eda-desc">Anthony carries nearly 2x Jane Doe's load and ~3.5x Harry's. This kind of skew doesn't show up in ticket counts alone — it only becomes visible when you aggregate by assignee and sort. This finding directly drove the assignee slicer in the internal dashboard.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="c2" height="190"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <div class="eda-card">
      <div class="eda-head">
        <div class="eda-title">Open Ticket Aging — SLA Risk Analysis</div>
        <div class="eda-desc">Right-skewed distribution with a long tail past 84 days (red). Bi-weekly bins were chosen to match a reasonable sprint-length resolution window. Tickets in the 98+ day bucket are almost certainly SLA violations and represent operational risk that wasn't being tracked before this pipeline existed.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="c3" height="190"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <div class="eda-card">
      <div class="eda-head">
        <div class="eda-title">SN to ADO Cross-System Traceability</div>
        <div class="eda-desc">78% of ServiceNow tickets could be matched to an ADO enhancement record by ID. The 22% gap wasn't silently dropped — it was flagged, documented in the MATLAB quality report, and excluded from the SQL schema load. Data integrity audit, not just cleaning.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="c4" height="190"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <div class="eda-card" style="grid-column:1/-1;">
      <div class="eda-head">
        <div class="eda-title">Monthly Enhancement Volume — Temporal Demand Pattern</div>
        <div class="eda-desc">Mid-year spike (June–August, highlighted) aligns with DEN's peak air traffic season — operational pressure on the airport translates directly into increased IT enhancement demand. This seasonal pattern is the kind of insight that drives quarterly staffing and backlog planning, and it was invisible before the datasets were merged.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="c5" height="140"></canvas></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
</div>

<!-- DASHBOARDS -->
<div class="wrap">
<section class="section reveal">
  <p class="sec-label">Output</p>
  <h2 class="sec-title">Power BI Dashboards</h2>
  <p class="sec-body">Both dashboards were built on the SQL schema — not on raw CSVs. The distinction matters: schema-backed dashboards don't break on refresh and support multi-user querying outside Power BI.</p>

  <div class="dash-pair" style="margin-top:40px;">
    <div>
      <span class="dash-label">01 &mdash; Internal View</span>
      <div class="dash-title">Company's Perspective</div>
      <div class="dash-sub">Tracks enhancement states, assignee workloads, completion % by enhancement ID, and customer SN distribution. Sliceable by ADO assignee.</div>
      <div class="dash-frame">
        <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Internal Dashboard" />
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <span class="dash-label">02 &mdash; Customer View</span>
      <div class="dash-title">Client's Perspective</div>
      <div class="dash-sub">Surfaces feature request progress, user story completion rates, and enhancement state breakdowns — designed for external stakeholder consumption, not internal ops.</div>
      <div class="dash-frame">
        <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Customer Dashboard" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="insights">
    <div class="ins">
      <span class="ins-t">Workload Imbalance</span>
      <span class="ins-b">Anthony's load is nearly 2x the next assignee. Invisible in raw data, obvious in aggregate. The dashboard makes it a one-glance finding for any manager.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="ins">
      <span class="ins-t">Backlog Health</span>
      <span class="ins-b">56.9% closed is good. But 32% active+new means the team is absorbing new work faster than it's clearing the queue — a capacity signal worth monitoring.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="ins">
      <span class="ins-t">Customer Prioritization</span>
      <span class="ins-b">Tracy Chapman holds ~20 assigned SN tickets — nearly 3x the next customer. Cross-system merge made this visible for the first time.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="ins">
      <span class="ins-t">Awaiting Customer Gap</span>
